#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/xml-guide.xml:363
#, no-wrap
msgid "  &lt;path&gt;, &lt;c&gt;, &lt;b&gt;, &lt;e&gt;, &lt;sub&gt; and &lt;sup&gt;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xml-guide.xml:368
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>&lt;path&gt;</c>, <c>&lt;c&gt;</c>, <c>&lt;b&gt;</c>, <c>&lt;e&gt;</c>,\n"
"<c>&lt;sub&gt;</c> and <c>&lt;sup&gt;</c> elements can be used inside any child\n"
"<c>&lt;body&gt;</c> tag, except for <c>&lt;pre&gt;</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xml-guide.xml:374
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>&lt;path&gt;</c> element is used to mark text that refers to an\n"
"<e>on-disk file</e> -- either an <e>absolute or relative path</e>, or a \n"
"<e>simple filename</e>. This element is generally rendered with a mono spaced \n"
"font to offset it from the standard paragraph type.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xml-guide.xml:381
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>&lt;c&gt;</c> element is used to mark up a <e>command</e> or <e>user\n"
"input</e>.  Think of <c>&lt;c&gt;</c> as a way to alert the reader to something\n"
"that they can type in that will perform some kind of action.  For example, all\n"
"the XML tags displayed in this document are enclosed in a <c>&lt;c&gt;</c>\n"
"element because they represent something that the user could type in that is\n"
"not a path.  By using <c>&lt;c&gt;</c> elements, you'll help your readers\n"
"quickly identify commands that they need to type in.  Also, because\n"
"<c>&lt;c&gt;</c> elements are already offset from regular text, <e>it is rarely\n"
"necessary to surround user input with double-quotes</e>. For example, don't\n"
"refer to a \"<c>&lt;c&gt;</c>\" element like I did in this sentence.  Avoiding\n"
"the use of unnecessary double-quotes makes a document more readable -- and \n"
"adorable!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xml-guide.xml:396
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As you might have guessed, <c>&lt;b&gt;</c> is used to <b>boldface</b> some\n"
"text.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xml-guide.xml:401
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>&lt;e&gt;</c> is used to apply emphasis to a word or phrase; for example:\n"
"I <e>really</e> should use semicolons more often.  As you can see, this text is\n"
"offset from the regular paragraph type for emphasis.  This helps to give your\n"
"prose more <e>punch</e>!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xml-guide.xml:408
#, no-wrap
msgid "The <c>&lt;sub&gt;</c> and <c>&lt;sup&gt;</c> elements are used to specify\n"
msgstr ""

